    "severity": "high",
    "message": "get_stock now hard-depends on a `reserved_count` key in the inventory response, but the committed consumer pact does not declare it. The consumer test (tests/functional/test_consumer_inventory.py) sets `.with_body({\"item_id\": match.int(1), \"in_stock\": match.int(5)})` with no `reserved_count`, so the Pact mock server returns no such key and `int(data[\"reserved_count\"])` raises KeyError when the contract is exercised. The change's own comment admits the field is \"not declared in the pact interaction.\" Because reserved_count is absent from the pact, the provider is under no contractual obligation to return it and provider-verification CI cannot catch its removal/absence — the consumer breaks in production with a green pipeline. A consumer that relies on a field MUST pin it in the pact.",
    "suggestion": "Add `reserved_count` to the consumer pact response body (e.g. `.with_body({\"item_id\": match.int(1), \"in_stock\": match.int(5), \"reserved_count\": match.int(0)})`) and regenerate/republish pacts/demo-inventory.json so the new dependency is part of the consumer-driven contract and gets provider-verified."
